    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>If the Shoe Doesn't Fit, Why Wear It?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sue K Levine, commenting on Deborah L Rhode's Oct 18 Op-Ed on uncomfortable women's shoes, says women should not give in to designers who cannot combine style and comfort; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Step, Wince, Step, Wince,'' by Deborah L. Rhode (Op-Ed, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Step, Wince, Step, Wince,'' by Deborah L. Rhode (Op-Ed, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>As a woman who has given up unwearable shoes for the plain, flat, black shoe (that comes in all colors), I will never understand why any woman would give in to designers who can't seem to combine style and comfort.</p>
        <p>Clothing designers seem to have come to terms with women who love style but who may wear a size 20. Why can't shoe designers make the same compromises and design shoes that are stylish and comfortable? I bet that women would buy a pair in every color.</p>
        <p>SUE K. LEVINE  Cherry Hill, N.J., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
